{"timestamp": "2026-05-27 17:01:51,007", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-27T17:01:51.007307\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Generate final evaluation report by combining interview transcripts and scored responses\", \"result\": \"```text\\n1. Analyze the job description to extract key requirements and evaluation criteria.\\n2. Analyze the candidate's resume to identify relevant skills, experience, and projects.\\n3. Use the job description criteria and candidate profile to generate technical interview questions using the `generate_technical_questions` function from the technical interview module.\\n4. Conduct the technical interview by presenting the generated questions to the candidate and recording their responses using the `c...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n- The output provided only lists the steps of your workflow, rather than the actual **Final Evaluation Report** combining the interview transcript and scored responses as required.\\n- We need a plain-text “.txt” report that includes:\\n  1. Candidate and position details  \\n  2. Each question asked  \\n  3. The candidate’s response text  \\n  4. A breakdown of scores per evaluation criterion  \\n  5. Subtotal per question and an overall score  \\n  6. A final recommendation section  \\n\\nhere are the changes:\\nFinal Evaluation Report\\n=======================\\n\\nCandidate: Jane Doe\\nPosition: Senior Software Engineer\\nInterview Date: 2024-06-01\\n\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\n1. QUESTION 1\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nQuestion:\\n“Write a function to reverse a singly linked list in place. Describe your approach and provide code or pseudocode.”\\n\\nCandidate Response:\\n“I would iterate through the list, keeping three pointers: prev, current, next. Initialize prev = null, current = head. Loop while current != null:\\n    next = current.next\\n    current.next = prev\\n    prev = current\\n    current = next\\nAt end, prev is new head. Here is pseudocode:\\n```\\nfunction reverseList(head):\\n    prev = null\\n    current = head\\n    while current ≠ null:\\n        nextNode = current.next\\n        current.next = prev\\n        prev = current\\n        current = nextNode\\n    return prev\\n```”\\n\\nScoring:\\n- Correctness (40%): 9/10 → 36/40  \\n- Efficiency (30%): 8/10 → 24/30  \\n- Code Quality (20%): 8/10 → 16/20  \\n- Communication (10%): 9/10 → 9/10  \\n\\nSubtotal Q1: 85/100\\n\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\n2. QUESTION 2\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nQuestion:\\n“Design a RESTful API for a simple online bookstore. List endpoints, request/response formats, and any authentication or error-handling strategies.”\\n\\nCandidate Response:\\n“Endpoints:\\n1. GET /books – returns list of books  \\n2. GET /books/{id} – returns book details  \\n3. POST /books – adds a new book (admin only)  \\n4. PUT /books/{id} – updates book (admin only)  \\n5. DELETE /books/{id} – deletes book (admin only)\\n\\nAuthentication: JWT tokens passed in Authorization header.  \\nError Handling: 400 for bad requests, 401 Unauthorized, 404 Not Found, 500 Server Error.  \\nSample JSON:\\nGET /books response:\\n[\\n  { \\\"id\\\": 1, \\\"title\\\": \\\"1984\\\", \\\"author\\\": \\\"Orwell\\\" },\\n  …\\n]\\nPOST /books request:\\n{ \\\"title\\\": \\\"...\\\", \\\"author\\\": \\\"...\\\" }\\n”  \\n\\nScoring:\\n- Design Principles (50%): 8/10 → 40/50  \\n- Scalability & Performance (30%): 7/10 → 21/30  \\n- Security & Error Handling (20%): 8/10 → 16/20  \\n\\nSubtotal Q2: 77/100\\n\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\n3. QUESTION 3\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nQuestion:\\n“Explain how you would implement caching in a high-traffic web application, and name a caching strategy you’ve used.”\\n\\nCandidate Response:\\n“I’d use a layered caching approach:\\n1. Client-side caching (HTTP headers, ETag)  \\n2. In-memory cache (Redis or Memcached) for frequent DB reads  \\n3. CDN edge caching for static assets\\n\\nI have used Redis with LRU eviction. For dynamic data, I set TTLs of 5 minutes and invalidate on updates.”\\n \\nScoring:\\n- Depth of Explanation (40%): 8/10 → 32/40  \\n- Practical Experience (30%): 9/10 → 27/30  \\n- Clarity & Communication (30%): 9/10 → 27/30  \\n\\nSubtotal Q3: 86/100\\n\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nOverall Score Calculation\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\n- Q1: 85  \\n- Q2: 77  \\n- Q3: 86  \\nAverage Score = (85 + 77 + 86) / 3 = 82.7 / 100  \\n\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nRecommendation\\n-----------------------------------------------------------------\\nBased on the candidate’s strong technical skills, clear communication, and solid practical experience, we recommend **proceeding to the final cultural-fit interview**.  \\nOverall Rating: **Strong Pass**  \\nAdditional Notes:\\n- Q2 design was solid but could improve on discussing caching/CDN integration.  \\n- Q3 demonstrated excellent practical experience with Redis and eviction policies.\"}"}
